1) Strategic Assessment:-

defination :-Strategic Assessment in project evaluation means analyzing whether a project aligns with the organization’s long-term goals, vision, and competitive strategy. It ensures the project is not only feasible but also strategically valuable.

🔹 Key Objectives
Check alignment with business goals
Ensure long-term benefits
Identify competitive advantage
Support decision-making

🔹 Example

A company planning to build an e-commerce website:
✔ Aligns with digital expansion strategy
✔ Meets growing online shopping demand
✔ Provides competitive advantage

🔹 Advantages
Better decision making
Reduces project failure
Ensures long-term success
Efficient use of resources

🔹 Disadvantages
Time-consuming
Requires expert analysis
May involve uncertainty 

2) Technical Assessment:-

defination:-Technical Assessment is the process of evaluating whether a project is technically feasible—i.e., 
            whether the required technology, tools, skills, and infrastructure are available to successfully complete the project.

🔹 Objectives
Check technical feasibility
Identify technology requirements
Ensure availability of resources & skills
Reduce technical risks 

🔹 Process
Identify technical requirements
Analyze available technology & tools
Evaluate team skills
Assess risks & limitations
Decide feasibility

🔹 Example
Building a Mutual Fund Web App (Next.js + Supabase):
✔ Technology available (Next.js, database)
✔ Team skilled in React
✔ Cloud hosting possible
✔ APIs for financial data available

🔹 Advantages
Reduces technical failure
Improves project quality
Helps in better planning
Ensures smooth implementation

🔹 Disadvantages
Requires expert knowledge
Time-consuming
Rapid tech changes can affect decisions

3) Cost–Benefit Analysis:- 

defination :-Cost–Benefit Analysis (CBA) is a technique used to compare the total expected costs of a project with its total expected benefits to determine whether the project is worthwhile.

🔹 Objective
Decide if project is profitable or not
Support investment decisions
Ensure maximum return with minimum cost

1. Types of Costs
Direct Costs – Development, hardware, software
Indirect Costs – Training, maintenance
One-time Costs – Setup cost
Recurring Costs – Monthly hosting, salaries
  
2. Types of Benefits
Tangible Benefits – Revenue, cost savings
Intangible Benefits – Brand value, customer satisfaction
Short-term Benefits – Immediate profit
Long-term Benefits – Future growth

3. Key Methods
Payback Period – Time required to recover investment
Net Present Value (NPV) – Present value of benefits minus costs
Return on Investment (ROI) – Profit earned from investment

4. Process
Identify all costs
Identify all benefits
Convert into monetary value
Compare costs and benefits
Make decision 

🔹 Example

Project: E-commerce Website Development
Cost = ₹1,00,000
Expected Benefit = ₹1,50,000
👉 Profit = ₹50,000
👉 ROI = 50% (project is beneficial)

🔹 Advantages
Helps in decision making
Simple and clear method
Improves financial planning

🔹 Disadvantages
Difficult to measure intangible benefits
Future estimates may be inaccurate
Time-consuming

4) Cash Flow Forecasting:- 

defination:-Cash Flow Forecasting is the process of estimating the inflow (cash coming in) and outflow (cash going out) of money in a project over a specific period of time.

🔹 Objectives
Ensure enough cash availability
Avoid cash shortages
Support financial planning
Improve decision-making

🔹 Process
Estimate cash inflows
Estimate cash outflows
Calculate net cash flow
Analyze monthly/yearly trends
Plan for surplus or shortage

🔹 Example

Month 1:
Inflow = ₹50,000
Outflow = ₹30,000
👉 Net Cash Flow = ₹20,000 (positive)

Month 2:
Inflow = ₹20,000
Outflow = ₹40,000
👉 Net Cash Flow = -₹20,000 (negative)

🔹 Advantages
Helps manage finances
Prevents cash shortage
Improves budgeting
Supports better planning

🔹 Disadvantages
Depends on estimates
May be inaccurate
Time-consuming

5) Cost–Benefit Evaluation Techniques:- 

  defination :-Cost–Benefit Evaluation Techniques are methods used to compare project costs and benefits to decide whether the project is financially viable and worth investing in.

1. Payback Period
Time required to recover the initial investment

📌 Example
Investment = ₹1,00,000
Annual Return = ₹25,000
👉 Payback Period = 4 years
  
2. Net Present Value (NPV)
Difference between present value of cash inflows and outflows

📌 Decision Rule
NPV > 0 → Accept project
NPV < 0 → Reject project

3. Return on Investment (ROI)
Measures profitability of investment

4. Benefit–Cost Ratio (BCR)
Ratio of total benefits to total costs

📌 Decision Rule
BCR > 1 → Accept
BCR < 1 → Reject
  
5. Internal Rate of Return (IRR)
Rate at which NPV becomes zero

📌 Decision Rule
IRR > Required rate → Accept
IRR < Required rate → Reject

🔹 Advantages
Helps in better financial decisions
Easy comparison of multiple projects
Improves investment planning

🔹 Disadvantages
Based on estimates
Complex calculations (NPV, IRR)
Ignores non-financial factors sometimes

6) Risk Evaluation:- 

defination:- Risk Evaluation is the process of identifying, analyzing, and assessing potential risks in a project to minimize their impact and ensure project success.

🔹 Objectives
Identify possible risks
Analyze impact and probability
Reduce uncertainty
Support better decision-making
  
🔹 Types of Risks
Technical Risk – New or complex technology may fail
Financial Risk – Budget issues or cost overruns
Schedule Risk – Project delays
Operational Risk – Process or system failures
Market Risk – Changes in demand or competition
Legal Risk – Regulatory or compliance issues

🔹 Risk Evaluation Process
Identify risks
Analyze likelihood (probability)
Assess impact (severity)
Prioritize risks
Plan mitigation strategies

🔹 Risk Assessment Matrix
High Probability + High Impact → Critical Risk
Low Probability + High Impact → Major Risk
High Probability + Low Impact → Moderate Risk
Low Probability + Low Impact → Low Risk 

🔹 Example
Project: E-commerce Website
Risk: Server crash during high traffic
Impact: Loss of customers and revenue
Solution: Use scalable cloud hosting

🔹 Advantages
Reduces project failure
Improves planning
Helps in decision making
Increases project success rate

🔹 Disadvantages
Time-consuming
Not all risks can be predicted
Requires expert judgment
